This folowing code is explanation :

  • matplotlib library to create a histogram for each numerical column in a DataFrame named 'housing'.
  • housing.hist(): This method generates histograms for all numerical columns in the DataFrame 'housing'.
  • figsize=(12, 10): This parameter sets the size of the figure (width, height) in inches. In this case, the figure will be 12 inches wide and 10 inches high.
  • bins=30: This parameter determines the number of bins (intervals) in the histogram. In this case, each histogram will have 30 bins.
  • edgecolor="pink": This parameter sets the color of the edges of the bars in the histogram to pink.
  • Adjusting Subplots> plt.subplots_adjust(): This function adjusts the subplot parameters.
    • hspace=0.7: This sets the height spacing between subplots to 0.7 times the height of one subplot. It creates vertical space between the histograms.
    • wspace=0.4: This sets the width spacing between subplots to 0.4 times the width of one subplot. It creates horizontal space between the histograms.

We can see that:

  • the dataset contains 20,640 samples and 8 features;

  • all features are numerical features encoded as floating number;

  • there is no missing values.

5.Summarize in a table, for each of the three models:¶

In [123]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

# Create a DataFrame to store the summary
summary_data = {
    'Model': ['Median Income', 'Population', 'Number of Households'],
    'Intercept': [],
    'Slope': [],
    'Mean Squared Error': [],
    'Mean Absolute Error': []
}

# Function to calculate metrics and update the summary
def update_summary(model, independent_variable, y_true):
    y_pred = model.predict(independent_variable)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)

    summary_data['Intercept'].append(model.intercept_)
    summary_data['Slope'].append(model.coef_[0])
    summary_data['Mean Squared Error'].append(mse)
    summary_data['Mean Absolute Error'].append(mae)

# Update summary for Median Income model
update_summary(model_income, X_income, y)

# Update summary for Population model
update_summary(model_population, X_population, y)

# Update summary for Number of Households model
update_summary(model_households, X_households, y)

# Create a DataFrame from the summary data
summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_data)

# Print the summary table
print(summary_df)

6.Plot the resulting line on top of the scatter data for each of the three models (three separate graphs) (1 point)¶

In [130]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# plot scatter data and regression line
def plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model, independent_variable, y_true, title):
    sns.scatterplot(x=independent_variable.iloc[:, 0], y=y_true, label='Actual Data' )
    # Regression line
    x_range = independent_variable.iloc[:, 0]
    y_pred = model.predict(independent_variable) 
    plt.plot(x_range, y_pred, color='orange', label='Regression Line')

    # Set plot properties
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(independent_variable.columns[0])
    plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Plot for Median Income model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_income, X_income, y, 'Median Income, Median House Value')

# Plot for Population model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_population, X_population, y, 'Population, Median House Value')

# Plot for Number of Households model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_households, X_households, y, 'Number of Households, Median House Value')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have already fitted the linear regression models
# model_income, model_population, model_households

# Function to plot scatter data and regression line
def plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model, independent_variable, y_true, title):
    # Scatter plot
    plt.scatter(x=independent_variable.iloc[:, 0], y=y_true, label='Actual Data')

    # Regression line
    x_range = independent_variable.iloc[:, 0]
    y_pred = model.predict(independent_variable)
    plt.plot(x_range, y_pred, color='red', label='Regression Line')

    # Set plot properties
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(independent_variable.columns[0])
    plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Plot for Median Income model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_income, X_income, y, 'Median Income, Median House Value')

# Plot for Population model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_population, X_population, y, 'Population, Median House Value')

# Plot for Number of Households model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_households, X_households, y, 'Households, Median House Value')

7.Provide a conclusion about the goodness-of-fit, and other insights you might have (1 point)¶

In Summary:¶

  • The goodness-of-fit analysis for three linear regression models revealed valuable insights into the relationships between independent variables (median income, population, and households) and the dependent variable (median house value) in the California Housing Prices Datasets.

Median Income, Median House Value:¶

  • The linear regression model demonstrated a positive correlation, indicating that as median income increase, median house value trends to rise. The model's goodness-of-fit, as indicated by low Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error(MAE), suggests that it provides a reliable approximation.

Population, Median House Value:¶

  • The regression analysis indicated a more nuanced relationship, with a less clear correlation between population and median house value. The model's goodness-of-fit metrics suggested moderate accuracy, highlighting potential complexities in the impact of population on housing prices.

Households, Median House Value:¶

  • The linear regression model for the number of households demonstrated a discernible negative correlation. As the number of households increases, the median house value tends to increase. The model's goodness-of-fit metrics indicated satisfactory performance.

In summary:¶

  • The linear regression models provide valuable insights into how specific factors influence housing prices. However, it's essential to acknowledge that other factors not considered in this analysis may contribute to variations in median house values. Further exploration and refinement of the models could enhance their predictive capabilities, leading to a more comprehensive understanding of the dataset.
